df = pd.read_csv("matches.csv", index_col=0)
pd.set_option('display.max_columns', 500)

Description of the Dataset¶

Every row is a match statistics for a particular team.

comp: Competition

round: What week the game is played in

venue: where game is played at for the team column.

result: result of the match {W: Win, D: Draw, L: Loss}

gf: Goals scored for the team

ga: Goals scored against the team

opponent: Opposistion team name

xg: Expected goals scored

xga: Expected goals scored against the team

poss: % of possession a team has during the game

attendance: Amount of people attending the game

captain: Captain of the team during that match for the team column

formation: Team Formation used for the column team during that match

referee: The name of the referee for that match

sh: Shots taken for the team

sot: Shots on target for the team

dist: Average distance, in yards, from goal of all shots taken

fk: Freekicks taken for the team

pk: Penalty kicks made for the team

pkatt: Penalty kicks made for the team

season: Year of season

team: team for the match

def Weekend(dayNum):
    if dayNum == 6:
        return 1
    elif dayNum == 5:
        return 1
    else:
        return 0
df['Weekend?'] = df['dayNum'].apply(Weekend)
#Decides if the day is a weekend or not

def resultnum(result):
    if result == 'W':
        return 1
    elif result == 'D':
        return 0.5
    else:
        return 0
df['Result Number'] = df['result'].apply(resultnum)
#Turns W,D,L into numerical numbers

def Zeroone(Goals):
    if Goals <= 1:
        return 1
    else:
        return 0
df['Low Scoring Game'] = df['Total Goals'].apply(Zeroone)

Insight 3 (ML): What factors affect season position?¶

To Club Owners: Factors such as Net Transfer Count, Net Spending, Win count, Draw count, Loss count, Goals for, Goals Against, Goal Differntial, and the amount of points you gain in the season determine your position at the end of the season.

Dataset ("premier-league.csv") Description¶

The data set has:

• One row for each transfer made within the Premier league from 1992 to 2022
• The following columns: club_name, player_name, age, position, club_involved_name, fee, transfer_movement, transfer_period, fee_cleaned (fee without currency symbol), league_name, year, and season.

#Changing Season format to match "EPL Standings 2000-2022.csv" Season Column
def formatchange(Season):
    if Season == '2000/2001':
        return '2000-01'
    elif Season == '2001/2002':
        return '2001-02'
    elif Season == '2002/2003':
        return '2002-03'
    elif Season == '2003/2004':
        return '2003-04'
    elif Season == '2004/2005':
        return '2004-05'
    elif Season == '2005/2006':
        return '2005-06'
    elif Season == '2006/2007':
        return '2006-07'
    elif Season == '2007/2008':
        return '2007-08'
    elif Season == '2008/2009':
        return '2008-09'
    elif Season == '2009/2010':
        return '2009-10'
    elif Season == '2010/2011':
        return '2010-11'
    elif Season == '2011/2012':
        return '2011-12'
    elif Season == '2012/2013':
        return '2012-13'
    elif Season =='2013/2014':
        return '2013-14'
    elif Season =='2014/2015':
        return '2014-15'
    elif Season =='2015/2016':
        return '2015-16'    
    elif Season =='2016/2017':
        return '2016-17'
    elif Season =='2017/2018':
        return '2017-18'
    elif Season =='2018/2019':
        return '2018-19'
    elif Season =='2019/2020':
        return '2019-20'
    elif Season =='2020/2021':
        return '2020-21'
    elif Season =='2021/2022':
        return '2021-22'
    else:
        return 'N/A'

Dataset ( "EPL Standings 2000-2022.csv") description¶

Meaning of each column :

Season -- Year in which the league was

Pos -- Team position in the league

Team -- Team name

Pld -- Games played

W -- Games won

D -- Games tied

L -- Games lost

GF -- Goals for

GA -- Goals against

GD -- Goal difference

Pts -- Points won (Win = 3 pts, D= 1pt, L = 0pts)

Qualification or relegation -- Qualification to Europe Cups or relegation to Football League First Division

Each row represents a team and their statisitcs within a particular season. n.

# Decrease the nunique number
def Qual_Reg_Changes(Qual_Reg_String):
    if Qual_Reg_String.startswith('Qualification for the Champions League'):
        return "Champions League"
    elif 'relegation'in Qual_Reg_String:
        return "Relegation"
    elif 'Relegation'in Qual_Reg_String:
        return "Relegation"
    elif Qual_Reg_String.startswith('Qualification for the Europa League'):
        return "Europa League"
    elif Qual_Reg_String.startswith('Qualification for the UEFA Cup'):
        return "Europa League"
    else:
        return 'N/A'
df['Qual_Reg'] = df['Qual_Reg'].apply(Qual_Reg_Changes)

Managerial Insights¶

Insight #1: Investing in home venue environments/ambience could be conducive to on-field success. Additionally filling stadiums to 45,000 will lead to more goals and satisifed fans, who are more likely to engage with the club further in the future.

Insight #2: Exploring ways to minimize the effects of winter could lead to more goals and more entertainment for fans/consumers. A potential solution is to change the season months, so there are less winter months in the season.

Insight #3: There are many different ways to become 1st place in the league, but important factors include gaining more than 79 points and winning more than 19 games. Once a team is able to achieve those stats, other factors stated in the ML decision tree will get you to a 1st place finish. Additionally selling more players than you buy and investing more money into your transfers while not gaining much money from transfers sold will contribute to a higher position.

This finding can be used as: Sell many of the low transfer valued players and bring in a few, but signifcantly higher valued players into the team could push your team to the top of the league. (Quanity vs Quality)

Conclusion¶

Given more time and capability, there are a few additions that would’ve improved the findings. The first is to have incorporated a detailed weather dataset. The reason for this is that it will allow to drill down and determine if specific types of weather (not just winter/non-winter) affect the amount of goals in a game. It would’ve also helped to have a more in-depth attendance dataset. The dataset used only provided total attendance. This would be helpful for the venue insight if there was specific information on the breakdown between home and away fans in fan attendance.
